I've been using the app for several months, ever since the VA shipped me a new Guide Me meter. The linkup between the phone and meter is pretty cool, and works well most of the time. When it doesn't, it's usually because my older LG v20 decided to take a break. The big weakness for me is reporting. I should be able to view category averages in-app, like Fasting, etc. When my healthcare provider asks me what my fasting average is, my response now is "Duh?" Then I start scrolling through all the entries and say, "Well, on this day it was X, and on this day it was Y." Give me a button to tap to show 30/90-day category averages; otherwise those categories and such are useless. For that matter, I should be able to see those same averages in the report I export. You're making this report useless for us to share with our care providers, because it's too much work to extract useful data from it. You let us enter all sorts of cool numbers, like basal, bolus, and so forth. But you don't give us an uesful way to view the data. So why should I enter all of those numbers. And there's really no need for the massive advertisement that takes up almost 1/4 of the first page. It stands to reason that if I've exported this report, then I know what mySugr Logbook is, so I don't need a big ad for it. My care providers don't need the add either, especially since there's a URL at the bottom of every page.

I'm sure the developer will claim that the frequent tests are needed to do the a1c estimate. However, the popup says that you need to take your BC at least 3 times a day, but if you skip a day or so, it is okay. Well, that doesn't appear to be true, as overnight, I will lose the a1c function. This app is indeed appearing to be something to encourage the use of test strips, which are very expensive and not always covered by medical insurance. I must admit that I feel like so many companies play on diabetes sufferers by encouraging unrealistic BC / A1c levels. The levels seem to be lowered, making accomplishing healthy goals harder to obtain, and classifying some people as "diabetic", who in reality are not. The sales of diabetes drugs, test strips, lancets, and durable goods (test equipment) go up as the goal levels go down. Again, big pharma keeping those profits high. Google "top contributors to American Diabetes Association", and see how many big pharma donate to the ADA.

This app appears to be quite useful for recording information related to diabetes management. However, the reporting function has some serious shortcomings with regard to accuracy and how the stored data is reported. Despite having alerted the developer to this, the response has merely been to tell the user that the app is being used incorrectly. This is very unfortunate since, despite having gone to great lengths to provide very specific and clear information highlighting the error, the developers have failed to take the matter seriously and have merely blamed my blood sugar meter. This is in fact quite bizarre since my blood sugar meter does not connect with this app and all the data input has been manual and can clearly be checked when using the "export to Excel" function within the app. There are some other issues with the report where it doesn't always adopt the units specified during setup of the app so some elements of the reported data aren't much use unless the user wishes to convert them outside the app. Support from the developer has been a little hit and miss in terms of response to emails. However, the communication style is extremely casual and more appropriate to chatting with friends on social media than it is responding to customer concerns about defects within the app. Perhaps herein lies the root of the problem with the shortcomings of the app and the lack of maturity of approach to its development has lead to some unfortunate issues. It is a shame because the app has the potential to be better than any other used to date.

Traveled west  by 6 hours and and the app screwed up (superimposed) my data after the time change. There must be a better solution! Concretely: use UTC internally, get a continuous graph (without jump ing) in the app, and go into a new line in the report when turning the clock back, so you can keep the "1 line = 1 day" correspondence.  Another issue that could be improved:  Long acting insulin is not visible by default in the logbook, only when dragging an individual entry to the left. Maybe this is different on bigger screens (I have a 1920√ó1080 resolution), but in any case it is sub-optimal when one quickly wants to check whether one has entered the values already. There are several ways to solve this. For example, one could remove the column with the pictures, which are too small anyway to see anything. Or one could remove the vertical line with the dots, which serves no purpose at all. Or one could make everything a bit smaller.

My dog was just recently diagnosed with diabetes. It was scary enough to be responsible for injecting him with insulin 2x a day. But my vet also needed me to provide her with results of a 12 hour blood glucose curve. So I was not only faced with learning to do insulin injections, but also how to prick his paw, analyze the results and get the results of the test back to the vet in a timely fashion. I bought an Accu Vue blood tester, a new piece of equipment for me and was surprised to learn, when I got it home, that it had data reporting and supported wireless transmissions.   Now I am a 63 year old woman with an outdated computer programming background from the 80's. So when you asked me my opinion of your software I was delighted to respond.  I Loved that Sugr was so Simple to set-up and easy to understand ...  as in the  "keep it simple" phrase drilled into my head by my programming instructor.  I know that I am not a luddite but still, I do find that fear and anxiety can be an obstacle to learning. So thank-you for keeping it easy and allowing me the opportunity to amaze my vet with my ability to email her my dog's blood glucose curve. Apparently she usually receives notes scratched on a piece of scrap paper.  So Yayyy!!! Thanks again. You all deserve a cold one ... bottoms up!   Hugs from Kathy and Buddy in Revelstoke BC

MySugr has been a great tool for me in getting my bg readings under control. I have been using it for a year and a half and have brought my A1C down from a 9.1 to 6.6-7.1 over the past year. Ive tried a lot of Glucose tracking apps.  This one is the most complete.  Obviously designed by someone familiar with "the club".  The only thing I would really like to see is a food/nutrition database.  I am new to DB and do not yet have a handle on how many carbs everything is.  I use MyfitnessPal now to track food consumption.  It is perfect for inputting meals and spitting out how many carbs, sodium, fiber, protein I am getting per meal/day/week.  But; it cannot track heath issues like glucose.  So I am using both this app to track Sugar and MyFitnessPal to track food.   If MySugr could add a food database similar to how myfitnesspal does it; you would have a near perfect app!
